Let $\sqrt{2x + 1},$ $\sqrt{2y + 1},$ and $\sqrt{2z + 1}$ be positive real numbers whose sum is constant.<</think>

We apply the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality, which is a special case of the Triangle Inequality for $$\sqrt{x^{2}_{i}+y^{2}_{i}}\le\sqrt{x^{2}}+\sqrt{y^{2}}.\tag*{with} (x_{i},y_{i})=(\sqrt{2x+1},\sqrt{1})$$ to obtain that the sum of the $\sqrt{2x + 1},$ $\sqrt{2y + 1},$ and $\sqrt{2z + 1}$ is less than or equal to
\begin{align*}
\sqrt{(\sqrt{2x+1})^{2}+(\sqrt{1})^{2}}+\sqrt{(\sqrt{2y+1})^{2}+(\sqrt{1})^{2}}&+\sqrt{(\sqrt{2z+1})^{2}+(\sqrt{1})^{2}} \\ \\
&\le\sqrt{\sqrt{4x^{2}+2x+1}+\sqrt{2y+2}}+\sqrt{2z+2}
\end{align*}
Now, this simplifies to Chebyshev's Inequality, which is a special case of the Cauchy-Schwarz Inequality for $$1^{2}\cdot (\sqrt{x}+\sqrt{y}+\sqrt{z})\le(\sqrt{1^{2}}+\sqrt{1^{2}}+\sqrt{1^{2}})(\sqrt{x}+\sqrt{y}+\sqrt{z}).$$ It follows that the value in the exponent of our original inequality is less than or equal to $3\cdot\sqrt{\sqrt{9x^{2}+2x+2y+2}}.$

We factor the radicand inside of $\sqrt{}$ to obtain that this value is less than or equal to $3\cdot\sqrt{\sqrt{(2x+2)(2y+2)}}=\sqrt{27}=\boxed{3\sqrt{3}}.$ You do not need the triangle inequality at all, but noting the $8$ in the problem is a red herring. We get $\sqrt{3\cdot27}.$
